{"title_page": "Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = File:First Female Medical College of Pennsylvania Building.JPG\n| image_upright = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = The first building to house the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania\n| latin_name = \n| other_name = WMCP\n| former_name = Female Medical College of Pennsylvania, Medical College of Pennsylvania\n| motto = \n| motto_lang = \n| mottoeng = \n| top_free_label = \n| top_free = \n| type = \n| established = {{start date| 1850}}\n| closed = {{end date| 1970}} (became co-ed Medical College of Pennsylvania)\n| founder = \n| parent = \n| affiliation = \n| religious_affiliation = \n| academic_affiliation = \n| endowment = \n| budget = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| chairman = \n| chairperson = \n| chancellor = \n| president = \n| vice-president = \n| superintendent = \n| vice_chancellor = \n| provost = \n| rector = \n| principal = \n| dean = \n| director = \n| head_label = \n| head = \n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students = \n| undergrad = \n| postgrad = \n| doctoral = \n| other = \n| address = <!-- Please discuss before using -->\n| city = Philadelphia\n| state = Pennsylvania\n| province = \n| country = \n| postcode = <!--or, postalcode or zipcode-->\n| coordinates = <!-- {{Coord}} -->\n| campus = \n| language = \n| free_label = \n| free = \n| free_label2 = \n| free2 = \n| colors = <!--or, colours= -->\n| athletics = \n| sports = \n| athletics_nickname = <!--or,  sports_nickname= -->\n| sporting_affiliations = \n| mascot = <!--or, mascots= -->\n| sports_free_label = \n| sports_free = \n| sports_free_label2 = \n| sports_free2 = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\nThe '''Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania''' (WMCP) was founded in 1850, and was the second medical institution in the world established to train women in medicine to earn the M.D. degree. The [[New England Female Medical College]] had been established two years earlier in 1848.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=1}}</ref> Originally called the '''Female Medical College of Pennsylvania,''' the college changed its name in 1867 to Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania in 1867. The associated [[Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia]] was founded in 1861. Upon deciding to admit men in 1970, the college was renamed as the '''Medical College of Pennsylvania''' (MCP) .\n\nIn 1930, the college opened its new campus in [[East Falls, Philadelphia|East Falls]], which combined teaching and the clinical care of a hospital in one overall facility. It was the first purpose-built hospital in the nation. In 1993, the college and hospital merged with [[Hahnemann Medical School]]. In 2003, the two colleges were absorbed by the [[Drexel University College of Medicine]].\n\n== Founding ==\nSmedley's ''History of the Underground Railroad'' cites [[Bartholomew Fussell|Dr. Bartholomew Fussell]] with proposing, in 1846, the idea for a college that would train female doctors. It was a tribute to his departed sister, who Bartholomew believed could have been a doctor if women had been given the opportunity at that time. Her daughter, [[Graceanna Lewis]], was to become one of the first woman scientists in the United States. At a meeting at his house, The Pines, in [[Kennett Square, Pennsylvania]], Fussell invited five doctors to carry out his idea. The doctors invited were: Edwin Fussell (Bartholomew's nephew) M.D., Franklin Taylor, M.D., Ellwood Harvey, M.D., Sylvester Birdsall, M.D., and Dr. Ezra Michener. Graceanna also attended. Dr. Fussell would support the college, but had little to do with it after it started in 1850 in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Smedley 1883\">{{cite book |last=Smedley |first=Dr. Robert C. |year=1883 |url=http://deila.dickinson.edu/cdm/ref/collection/slaverya/id/48198 |title=History of the Underground Railroad |location=Mechanicsburg, PA |publisher=Stackpole Books |page=268  |oclc=186383647}}</ref>\n\nEllwood Harvey (who attended the 1846 meeting, but did not start teaching at the college until 1852), helped keep the school alive, along with Edwin Fussell. Dr. Harvey not only taught a full course load but took on a second load when another professor backed out.\n\nDr. Harvey also continued his medical practice. Among his patients were [[William Still]] and his family. Still, a renowned Philadelphia abolitionist became a historian of the Underground Railroad after keeping extensive records of fugitive slaves aided in Philadelphia rescues.\n\nHarvey was later sued for libel by Dr. Longshore, an instructor at the college who was forced out. Longshore started a rival women's medical college at the [[Penn Medical University]]. Using his previous connections from the Female Medical College, Longshore began to raise money for his own college.\n\n[[Clara Marshall]] (1847\u20131931) graduated from the Medical College of Pennsylvania. She served as Dean from 1888 to 1917 and thought of Edwin Fussell as the founder of the school.<ref name=Rutg_p10>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title='A new and untried course': Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=10}}</ref> Other students credited Joseph S. Longshore and William J. Mullen as being primary founders in terms of their contributions.<ref name=Rutg_p10 /> Most considered these three men, whether official founder or not, to be instrumental in the creation of the Female Medical College of Pennsylvania.<ref name=Rutg_p10 />\n\nThe [[Feminist Movement]] during the early to mid [[19th century]] generated support for the Female Medical College of Pennsylvania. The [[Society of Friends]] in Philadelphia, a large group of [[Quakers]], were supportive of the women's rights movements and the development of the Female MCP.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=6}}</ref>\n\nMCP was initially located in the rear of 229 Arch Street, Philadelphia (the address was later changed to 627 Arch Street when Philadelphia renumbered streets in 1858).<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=13}}</ref> In July 1861, the board of corporators of the Female Medical College of Pennsylvania chose to rent rooms for the College from the Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia on North College Avenue.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=22}}</ref>\n\n==Deans of the College==\nThe first dean of what was then known as the Female Medical College was a man: [[Nathaniel R. Mosely]], appointed 1850\u20131856.<ref>{{cite news|title=Female physicians and female medical college|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JtY_f2rwE6oC&pg=PA28|accessdate=22 December 2016|work=Ohio Cultivator|page=28|issue=VIII|date=1852}}</ref> The second dean was also a man, [[Edwin B. Fussell]], who held the position from 1856 to 1866.<ref name=\"Kelly\">{{cite book|last1=Kelly|first1=Howard Atwood|title=American Medical Biographies|date=1920|publisher=The Norman, Remington Company|location=Baltimore, M.D.|isbn=9781235663499|pages=[https://archive.org/details/b31367069/page/418 418]\u2013419|url=https://archive.org/details/b31367069|accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom then on, the Woman's College had a long history of female deans, lasting almost 100 years. The first woman to be a dean of this (or any) medical school was [[Ann Preston]].<ref name=\"Mandell\">{{cite web|last1=Mandell|first1=Melissa M.|title=Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania|url=http://philadelphiaencyclopedia.org/archive/womans-medical-college-of-pennsylvania/|website=The Encyclopedia of Greater Philadelphia|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> The following women were deans of the college in the years stated:\n\n* 1866\u20131872, [[Ann Preston]]<ref name=\"Fay\">{{cite journal|last1=Fay|first1=MS|title=Ann Preston: Dean of the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1866-1872|journal=Transactions & Studies of the College of Physicians of Philadelphia|date=July 1965|volume=33|pages=43\u20138|pmid=14344617}}</ref>\n* 1872\u20131874, [[Emeline Horton Cleveland]]<ref name=\"Cleveland\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Emeline Horton Cleveland|url=https://cfmedicine.nlm.nih.gov/physicians/biography_64.html|website=Changing the face of medicine|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 1874\u20131886, [[Rachel Bodley]]<ref name=\"PACSCL Bodley\">{{cite web|title=Rachel L. Bodley papers 291|url=http://dla.library.upenn.edu/dla/pacscl/detail.html?id=PACSCL_DUCOM_WMSC420xml|website=PACSCL Finding Aids|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 1886/1888\u20131917, [[Clara Marshall]]<ref name=\"Marshall\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Clara Marshall|url=https://cfmedicine.nlm.nih.gov/physicians/biography_214.html|website=Changing the face of medicine|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 1917\u20131940, [[Martha Tracy]]<ref name=\"Rogers\">{{cite journal|last1=Rogers|first1=Fred B.|title=Martha Tracy (1876\u20131942): Exceptional Woman of Public Health|journal=Archives of Environmental Health: An International Journal|date=December 1964|volume=9|issue=6|pages=819\u2013821|doi=10.1080/00039896.1964.10663931|pmid=14203108}}</ref> (Henry Jump served as interim dean during Tracy's sabbatical.)\n* 1940/1943\u20131943/1946, [[Margaret Craighill]]\n* 1946\u20131963, [[Marion Spencer Fay]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Marion Spencer Fay Award|url=http://drexel.edu/medicine/Community-Engagement/Institute-for-Womens-Health-and-Leadership/Programs/Marion-Spencer-Fay-Award/|website=Institute for Women's Health and Leadership|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nNo woman was found to replace Marion Fay. After her, the position of dean was held by [[Glen R. Leymaster]] from 1964\u20131970,<ref>{{cite journal|title=News and Comment|journal=Archives of Environmental Health: An International Journal|date=April 1964|volume=8|issue=4|pages=625\u2013628|doi=10.1080/00039896.1964.10663727}}</ref> at which time the institution became known as the [[Medical College of Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dixon|first1=Mark|title=The hidden history of Chester County : lost tales from the Delaware and Brandywine Valleys|date=2011|publisher=History Press|location=Charleston, SC|isbn=978-1609490737}}</ref>\n\n== Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia ==\n{{main|Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia}}\nIn part to provide clinical experience for WMC students, a group of [[Quakers|Quaker]] women, particularly [[Ann Preston]], founded the Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia in 1861.<ref name=Rutg_p24>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998 |year=2000 |publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=24}}</ref> In 1929, the West Philadelphia Hospital for Women merged with the Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia, retaining the latter's name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_256.html|title=Dr. Ann Preston|date=2015|website=National Library of Medicine|access-date=May 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Issues in clinical training ==\nThe Female Medical College of Pennsylvania faced difficulties in providing clinical training for its students.<ref name=\"Peitzman 2000 p. 78\">Peitzman (2000), ''A New and Untried Course'', p. 78</ref> Almost all medical institutions were confronted with the demand for more clinical practice due to the rise of surgery, physical diagnosis, and clinical specialties.<ref>Edward Atwater, \"'Making Fewer Mistakes': A History of Students and Patients,\" pp. 165-187, ''Bulletin of the History of Medicine'' 57, 1983</ref> During the 1880s, clinical instruction at the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania relied mainly on the demonstration clinics.<ref name=\"Peitzman 2000 p. 78\"/>\n\nIn 1887, [[Anna Broomall]], professor of [[obstetrics]] for the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania, established a [[maternity]] [[outpatient]] service in a poor area of South Philadelphia for the purpose of student education.<ref name=\"Peitzman 2000 p. 78\"/> By 1895, many students cared for three or four women who were giving birth.<ref>Peitzman (2000), ''A New and Untried Course'', p. 79</ref>\n\n== East Falls campus and Drexel University ==\nIn the late 1920s, the college raised money to build a new campus. Designed by Ritter & Shay, the most successful of the Philadelphia urban architecture firms in the 1920s, the East Falls Campus was the first purpose-built hospital in the nation. The design allowed both teaching and hospital care to take place in one facility, helping provide for more clinical care. Post-WWII housing shortages in the city were a catalyst for development of additions to the East Falls Campus, the first of which was the Ann Preston Building (designed by [[Thaddeus Longstreth]]), which provided housing and classrooms for student nurses.\n\n[[File:20091108 inq institut08-h.JPG|thumb|Falls Center]]\n[[File:Womans Medical College of Pennsylvania.jpeg|thumb|Front of the Falls Center]]\n\nToday, the building is known as the Falls Center. It is operated by [[Iron Stone Strategic Capital Partners]] as student housing, commercial space, and medical offices.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mastrull|first=Diane|title=Falls Center is still evolving/ The historic location of the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania is now becoming a medical and educational complex. The center continues to attract new tenants.|url=http://articles.philly.com/2009-11-08/business/25283331_1_tenants-vacant-office-space-search-for-new-space|work=Philly.com|accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993 the Medical College of Pennsylvania merged with [[Hahnemann Medical College]], retaining its Queen Lane campus. In 2003, the two medical colleges were absorbed as a part of [[Drexel University College of Medicine]], creating new opportunities for the large student body for clinical practice in settings ranging from urban hospitals to small rural practices.\n\n==Notable alumnae==\n{{Category see also|Category:Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania alumni}}The following is a list of Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania alumni (by century of graduation and in alphabetical order by last name) who are notable for their medical career.\n\n=== 19th century ===\n* [[Caroline Still Anderson]], (class of 1878) \n*[[Lucinda L. Combs|Dr. Lucinda L. Combs Strittmater]], first female physician to serve in China for the Women's Foreign Ministry Society\n* [[Anandi Gopal Joshi|Anandibai Gopal Joshi]],Class of 1886, First Female Doctor from India\n* [[Jessie Crawford Wilson]], (class of 1890) Medical missionary to Persia.\n* [[Alice Bennett]], (class of 1880), chief physician and first woman superintendent of the women's department of the [[Norristown State Hospital|State Hospital for the Insane]] in Norristown, Pennsylvania.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cfmedicine.nlm.nih.gov/physicians/biography_32.html|title=Dr. (Mary) Alice Bennett|website=Changing the Face of Medicine|publisher=U.S. National Library of Medicine|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> \n* [[Elizabeth D. A. Cohen]], (class of 1857) first woman licensed to practice medicine in the state of [[Louisiana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/elizabeth-d-a-magnus-cohen|title=Elizabeth D.A. Magnus Cohen|website=JewishVirtualLibrary.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>\n* [[Rebecca Cole]], (class of 1867) the second African-American female physician in the United States.\n*[[Lucinda L. Combs]], (class of 1870) first female medical missionary in China, started first Women's Hospital in [[Peking]].\n* [[Halle Tanner Dillon Johnson]] the first female African-American doctor in [[Alabama]].\n* [[Caroline Matilda Dodson]] {class of 1874} (1845\u20131898), physician\n* [[Matilda Evans]], (class of 1897) the first African-American female physician licensed to practice in [[South Carolina]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://drexel.edu/now/archive/2017/March/Women-Physicians/|title=Remembering the Pioneering Women From One of Drexel\u2019s Legacy Medical Colleges|last=Falcone|first=Alissa|date=March 27, 2017|work=DrexelNow|access-date=2017-10-13|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Louise Celia Fleming]] (class of 1895) the first African-American female to attend and graduate.<ref name=\"BlackPast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpast.org/aah/fleming-louise-celia-lulu-1862-1899|title=Fleming, Louise Celia \"Lulu\" (1862-1899)|website=BlackPast.org|accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Eliza Ann Grier]], (class of 1897)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drexel.edu/medicine/About/Diversity/Our-Diverse-History/|title=Drexel University School of Medicine|website=Our Diverse History}}</ref> the first African-American female physician licensed to practice in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Rosetta Sherwood Hall]], (class of 1889) American-born Canadian medical missionary and educator in Korea.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich|url-access=registration|title=Notable American Women: The Modern Period : a Biographical Dictionary|last=Sicherman|first=Barbara|last2=Hurd Green|first2=Carol|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1980|isbn=978-0674627338|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich/page/299 299]\u2013300}}</ref>\n* [[Susan Hayhurst]], (class of 1857) the first woman to receive a pharmacy degree in the United States<ref>{{Cite journal|year=1911|title=Susan Hayhurst|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D0kfAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32|journal=American Journal of Pharmacy|volume=83|pages=32\u201339|access-date=November 29, 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* [[Sabat Islambouli]], first licensed female doctor in [[Syria]]<ref name=\"Rao\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/08/19th-century-women-medical-school_n_5093603.html|title=Meet The Three Female Medical Students Who Destroyed Gender Norms A Century Ago|last1=Rao|first1=Mallika|date=September 16, 2014|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Halle Tanner Dillon Johnson]], (class of 1891) the first woman to become a doctor in Alabama.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Verina Morton Jones|Verina M. Harris Morton Jones]] (class of 1888), the first woman licensed to practice in [[Mississippi]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Agnes Kemp]] (1823\u20131908), (class of 1879) the first woman to practice medicine in Dauphin County, Pennsylvania<ref name=Abram>Abram Ruth J. ''Send Us a Lady Physician: Women Doctors in America, 1835-1920''. WW Norton & Company, 1985, pp. 218\u2013220.</ref>\n* [[Anna Sarah Kugler]] (class of 1879) was the first medical missionary of the [[Evangelical Lutheran General Synod of the United States of North America]] and served in India for 47 years.\n* [[Clara Marshall]] (class of 1875), dean of Woman's Medical College from 1888 to 1917<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PBj5-zHEMvoC&lpg=PA216&pg=PA216|title=Biographical Dictionary of Modern American Educators|last1=Ohles|first1=Frederik|last2=Ohles|first2=Shirley M.|last3=Ramsay|first3=John G.|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|year=1997|isbn=9780313291333|page=[https://archive.org/details/biographicaldict0000ohle/page/216 216]|chapter=Marshall, Clara|access-date=December 1, 2016|via=Google Books|url=https://archive.org/details/biographicaldict0000ohle/page/216}}</ref>\n* [[Lillie Rosa Minoka Hill|Lillie Rosa Minoka-Hill]], (class of 1899) the second Native American woman to earn a medical degree.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Keiko Okami]], one of the earliest licensed female doctors in [[Japan]], the first being [[Ogino Ginko]]<ref name=\"Rao\" />\n* [[Susan La Flesche Picotte]], (class of 1889) the first [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] female physician<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Clara Swain]], (class of 1869) the first female medical missionary to India from the United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philadelphiaencyclopedia.org/archive/womans-medical-college-of-pennsylvania/|title=Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania {{!}} Encyclopedia of Greater Philadelphia|website=philadelphiaencyclopedia.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref>\n* [[Jennie Kidd Trout]], (class of 1875) first female licensed medical doctor in [[Canada]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Charlotte Whitehead]] Ross, a Canadian female physician who practiced in Montreal and Manitoba in the late 1800s and early 1900s.\n* [[Harriot Kezia Hunt]], Honorable MD recipient, women's rights activist, teacher.\n* [[Elizabeth Reifsnyder]], (class of 1881) opened first woman's hospital in [[Shanghai]]\n* [[Lilian Welsh]] (class of 1889), physician and educator, advocate for public health and preventative medicine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://msa.maryland.gov/msa/educ/exhibits/womenshall/html/welsh.html|title=Lilian Welsh, M.D., Maryland Women's Hall of Fame|date=2017|website=Maryland State Archives, Maryland Commission for Women|access-date=2017-11-15}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Holloway Wilhite]] (class of 1856), physician and philanthropist\n\n=== 20th century ===\n* [[Myrtelle Canavan]] (class of 1905), early neuropathologist who first described a form of leukodystrophy that would eventually be named after her, [[Canavan's disease]]. \n* [[Ruth Bleier]], (class of 1949) [[neurophysiologist]], and one of the first feminist scholars to explore how gender biases have shaped [[biology]].\n* [[Rita Sapiro Finkler]], (class of 1915) Ukrainian-born endocrinologist, gynecologist and pediatrician\n* [[Saniya Habboub]], (class of 1931) Lebanese medical doctor.\n* [[Joanne Overleese]], general surgeon, as well as one of the few doctors to have played in All-American Girls Professional Baseball League history\n* [[:de:Eva Reich|Eva Reich]], Austrian-born pediatrician and internationally known lecturer, daughter of controversial psychoanalyst [[Wilhelm Reich|Dr. Wilhelm Reich]].<ref>[http://archive.boston.com/bostonglobe/obituaries/articles/2008/08/13/dr_eva_reich_84_lectured_on_fathers_controversial_work/ \"Dr. Eva Reich, 84; lectured on father's controversial work,\" Boston Globe] (from the Associated Press), August 13, 2008.</ref>\n* [[Patricia Robertson]], a [[NASA]] astronaut and physician.\n* [[Kazue Togasaki]], (class of 1933) one of the earliest women of Japanese ancestry to earn a medical degree in the United States.\n* [[Martha Tracy]] (class of 1904), dean of Woman's Medical College from 1917 to 1940\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of defunct medical schools in the United States]]\n* [[List of female scientists before the 20th century]]\n* [[Penn Medical University]]\n* [[Women in medicine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==Further research==\n* [http://archives.drexelmed.edu/ Archives at Drexel University College of Medicine]\n* [http://www.saadigitalarchive.org/search/women%27s%20medical%20college%20of%20pennsylvania Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania materials in the South Asian American Digital Archive (SAADA)]\n* {{Facebook|id=Dr-Ellwood-Harvey-Underground-Railroad-Conductor-108263902552865|name=Dr. Ellwood Harvey, Underground Railroad Conductor}}\n\n{{coord|40.01190|-75.18420|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-PA|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Former women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania| ]]\n[[Category:East Falls, Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = File:First Female Medical College of Pennsylvania Building.JPG\n| image_upright = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = The first building to house the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania\n| latin_name = \n| other_name = WMCP\n| former_name = Female Medical College of Pennsylvania, Medical College of Pennsylvania\n| motto = \n| motto_lang = \n| mottoeng = \n| top_free_label = \n| top_free = \n| type = \n| established = {{start date| 1850}}\n| closed = {{end date| 1970}} (became co-ed Medical College of Pennsylvania)\n| founder = \n| parent = \n| affiliation = \n| religious_affiliation = \n| academic_affiliation = \n| endowment = \n| budget = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| chairman = \n| chairperson = \n| chancellor = \n| president = \n| vice-president = \n| superintendent = \n| vice_chancellor = \n| provost = \n| rector = \n| principal = \n| dean = \n| director = \n| head_label = \n| head = \n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students = \n| undergrad = \n| postgrad = \n| doctoral = \n| other = \n| address = <!-- Please discuss before using -->\n| city = Philadelphia\n| state = Pennsylvania\n| province = \n| country = \n| postcode = <!--or, postalcode or zipcode-->\n| coordinates = <!-- {{Coord}} -->\n| campus = \n| language = \n| free_label = \n| free = \n| free_label2 = \n| free2 = \n| colors = <!--or, colours= -->\n| athletics = \n| sports = \n| athletics_nickname = <!--or,  sports_nickname= -->\n| sporting_affiliations = \n| mascot = <!--or, mascots= -->\n| sports_free_label = \n| sports_free = \n| sports_free_label2 = \n| sports_free2 = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\nThe '''Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania''' (WMCP) was founded in 1850, and was the second medical institution in the world established to train women in medicine to earn the M.D. degree. The [[New England Female Medical College]] had been established two years earlier in 1848.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=1}}</ref> Originally called the '''Female Medical College of Pennsylvania,''' the college changed its name in 1867 to Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania in 1867. The associated [[Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia]] was founded in 1861. Upon deciding to admit men in 1970, the college was renamed as the '''Medical College of Pennsylvania''' (MCP) .\n\nIn 1930, the college opened its new campus in [[East Falls, Philadelphia|East Falls]], which combined teaching and the clinical care of a hospital in one overall facility. It was the first purpose-built hospital in the nation. In 1993, the college and hospital merged with [[Hahnemann Medical School]]. In 2003, the two colleges were absorbed by the [[Drexel University College of Medicine]].\n\n== Founding ==\nSmedley's ''History of the Underground Railroad'' cites [[Bartholomew Fussell|Dr. Bartholomew Fussell]] with proposing, in 1846, the idea for a college that would train female doctors. It was a tribute to his departed sister, who Bartholomew believed could have been a doctor if women had been given the opportunity at that time. Her daughter, [[Graceanna Lewis]], was to become one of the first woman scientists in the United States. At a meeting at his house, The Pines, in [[Kennett Square, Pennsylvania]], Fussell invited five doctors to carry out his idea. The doctors invited were: Edwin Fussell (Bartholomew's nephew) M.D., Franklin Taylor, M.D., Ellwood Harvey, M.D., Sylvester Birdsall, M.D., and Dr. Ezra Michener. Graceanna also attended. Dr. Fussell would support the college, but had little to do with it after it started in 1850 in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Smedley 1883\">{{cite book |last=Smedley |first=Dr. Robert C. |year=1883 |url=http://deila.dickinson.edu/cdm/ref/collection/slaverya/id/48198 |title=History of the Underground Railroad |location=Mechanicsburg, PA |publisher=Stackpole Books |page=268  |oclc=186383647}}</ref>\n\nEllwood Harvey (who attended the 1846 meeting, but did not start teaching at the college until 1852), helped keep the school alive, along with Edwin Fussell. Dr. Harvey not only taught a full course load but took on a second load when another professor backed out.\n\nDr. Harvey also continued his medical practice. Among his patients were [[William Still]] and his family. Still, a renowned Philadelphia abolitionist became a historian of the Underground Railroad after keeping extensive records of fugitive slaves aided in Philadelphia rescues.\n\nHarvey was later sued for libel by Dr. Longshore, an instructor at the college who was forced out. Longshore started a rival women's medical college at the [[Penn Medical University]]. Using his previous connections from the Female Medical College, Longshore began to raise money for his own college.\n\n[[Clara Marshall]] (1847\u20131931) graduated from the Medical College of Pennsylvania. She served as Dean from 1888 to 1917 and thought of Edwin Fussell as the founder of the school.<ref name=Rutg_p10>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title='A new and untried course': Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=10}}</ref> Other students credited Joseph S. Longshore and William J. Mullen as being primary founders in terms of their contributions.<ref name=Rutg_p10 /> Most considered these three men, whether official founder or not, to be instrumental in the creation of the Female Medical College of Pennsylvania.<ref name=Rutg_p10 />\n\nThe [[Feminist Movement]] during the early to mid [[19th century]] generated support for the Female Medical College of Pennsylvania. The [[Society of Friends]] in Philadelphia, a large group of [[Quakers]], were supportive of the women's rights movements and the development of the Female MCP.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=6}}</ref>\n\nMCP was initially located in the rear of 229 Arch Street, Philadelphia (the address was later changed to 627 Arch Street when Philadelphia renumbered streets in 1858).<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=13}}</ref> In July 1861, the board of corporators of the Female Medical College of Pennsylvania chose to rent rooms for the College from the Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia on North College Avenue.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998|year=2000|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=22}}</ref>\n\n==Deans of the College==\nThe first dean of what was then known as the Female Medical College was a man: [[Nathaniel R. Mosely]], appointed 1850\u20131856.<ref>{{cite news|title=Female physicians and female medical college|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JtY_f2rwE6oC&pg=PA28|accessdate=22 December 2016|work=Ohio Cultivator|page=28|issue=VIII|date=1852}}</ref> The second dean was also a man, [[Edwin B. Fussell]], who held the position from 1856 to 1866.<ref name=\"Kelly\">{{cite book|last1=Kelly|first1=Howard Atwood|title=American Medical Biographies|date=1920|publisher=The Norman, Remington Company|location=Baltimore, M.D.|isbn=9781235663499|pages=[https://archive.org/details/b31367069/page/418 418]\u2013419|url=https://archive.org/details/b31367069|accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom then on, the Woman's College had a long history of female deans, lasting almost 100 years. The first woman to be a dean of this (or any) medical school was [[Ann Preston]].<ref name=\"Mandell\">{{cite web|last1=Mandell|first1=Melissa M.|title=Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania|url=http://philadelphiaencyclopedia.org/archive/womans-medical-college-of-pennsylvania/|website=The Encyclopedia of Greater Philadelphia|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> The following women were deans of the college in the years stated:\n\n* 1866\u20131872, [[Ann Preston]]<ref name=\"Fay\">{{cite journal|last1=Fay|first1=MS|title=Ann Preston: Dean of the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1866-1872|journal=Transactions & Studies of the College of Physicians of Philadelphia|date=July 1965|volume=33|pages=43\u20138|pmid=14344617}}</ref>\n* 1872\u20131874, [[Emeline Horton Cleveland]]<ref name=\"Cleveland\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Emeline Horton Cleveland|url=https://cfmedicine.nlm.nih.gov/physicians/biography_64.html|website=Changing the face of medicine|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 1874\u20131886, [[Rachel Bodley]]<ref name=\"PACSCL Bodley\">{{cite web|title=Rachel L. Bodley papers 291|url=http://dla.library.upenn.edu/dla/pacscl/detail.html?id=PACSCL_DUCOM_WMSC420xml|website=PACSCL Finding Aids|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 1886/1888\u20131917, [[Clara Marshall]]<ref name=\"Marshall\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Clara Marshall|url=https://cfmedicine.nlm.nih.gov/physicians/biography_214.html|website=Changing the face of medicine|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 1917\u20131940, [[Martha Tracy]]<ref name=\"Rogers\">{{cite journal|last1=Rogers|first1=Fred B.|title=Martha Tracy (1876\u20131942): Exceptional Woman of Public Health|journal=Archives of Environmental Health: An International Journal|date=December 1964|volume=9|issue=6|pages=819\u2013821|doi=10.1080/00039896.1964.10663931|pmid=14203108}}</ref> (Henry Jump served as interim dean during Tracy's sabbatical.)\n* 1940/1943\u20131943/1946, [[Margaret Craighill]]\n* 1946\u20131963, [[Marion Spencer Fay]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Marion Spencer Fay Award|url=http://drexel.edu/medicine/Community-Engagement/Institute-for-Womens-Health-and-Leadership/Programs/Marion-Spencer-Fay-Award/|website=Institute for Women's Health and Leadership|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nNo woman was found to replace Marion Fay. After her, the position of dean was held by [[Glen R. Leymaster]] from 1964\u20131970,<ref>{{cite journal|title=News and Comment|journal=Archives of Environmental Health: An International Journal|date=April 1964|volume=8|issue=4|pages=625\u2013628|doi=10.1080/00039896.1964.10663727}}</ref> at which time the institution became known as the [[Medical College of Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dixon|first1=Mark|title=The hidden history of Chester County : lost tales from the Delaware and Brandywine Valleys|date=2011|publisher=History Press|location=Charleston, SC|isbn=978-1609490737}}</ref>\n\n== Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia ==\n{{main|Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia}}\nIn part to provide clinical experience for WMC students, a group of [[Quakers|Quaker]] women, particularly [[Ann Preston]], founded the Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia in 1861.<ref name=Rutg_p24>{{cite book|last=Peitzman|first=Steven J.|title=A new and untried course : Woman's Medical College and Medical College of Pennsylvania, 1850 - 1998 |year=2000 |publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, N.J [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8135-2815-1|pages=24}}</ref> In 1929, the West Philadelphia Hospital for Women merged with the Woman's Hospital of Philadelphia, retaining the latter's name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_256.html|title=Dr. Ann Preston|date=2015|website=National Library of Medicine|access-date=May 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Issues in clinical training ==\nThe Female Medical College of Pennsylvania faced difficulties in providing clinical training for its students.<ref name=\"Peitzman 2000 p. 78\">Peitzman (2000), ''A New and Untried Course'', p. 78</ref> Almost all medical institutions were confronted with the demand for more clinical practice due to the rise of surgery, physical diagnosis, and clinical specialties.<ref>Edward Atwater, \"'Making Fewer Mistakes': A History of Students and Patients,\" pp. 165-187, ''Bulletin of the History of Medicine'' 57, 1983</ref> During the 1880s, clinical instruction at the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania relied mainly on the demonstration clinics.<ref name=\"Peitzman 2000 p. 78\"/>\n\nIn 1887, [[Anna Broomall]], professor of [[obstetrics]] for the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania, established a [[maternity]] [[outpatient]] service in a poor area of South Philadelphia for the purpose of student education.<ref name=\"Peitzman 2000 p. 78\"/> By 1895, many students cared for three or four women who were giving birth.<ref>Peitzman (2000), ''A New and Untried Course'', p. 79</ref>\n\n== East Falls campus and Drexel University ==\nIn the late 1920s, the college raised money to build a new campus. Designed by Ritter & Shay, the most successful of the Philadelphia urban architecture firms in the 1920s, the East Falls Campus was the first purpose-built hospital in the nation. The design allowed both teaching and hospital care to take place in one facility, helping provide for more clinical care. Post-WWII housing shortages in the city were a catalyst for development of additions to the East Falls Campus, the first of which was the Ann Preston Building (designed by [[Thaddeus Longstreth]]), which provided housing and classrooms for student nurses.\n\n[[File:20091108 inq institut08-h.JPG|thumb|Falls Center]]\n[[File:Womans Medical College of Pennsylvania.jpeg|thumb|Front of the Falls Center]]\n\nToday, the building is known as the Falls Center. It is operated by [[Iron Stone Strategic Capital Partners]] as student housing, commercial space, and medical offices.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mastrull|first=Diane|title=Falls Center is still evolving/ The historic location of the Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania is now becoming a medical and educational complex. The center continues to attract new tenants.|url=http://articles.philly.com/2009-11-08/business/25283331_1_tenants-vacant-office-space-search-for-new-space|work=Philly.com|accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993 the Medical College of Pennsylvania merged with [[Hahnemann Medical College]], retaining its Queen Lane campus. In 2003, the two medical colleges were absorbed as a part of [[Drexel University College of Medicine]], creating new opportunities for the large student body for clinical practice in settings ranging from urban hospitals to small rural practices.\n\n==Notable alumnae==\n{{Category see also|Category:Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania alumni}}The following is a list of Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania alumni (by century of graduation and in alphabetical order by last name) who are notable for their medical career.\n\n=== 19th century ===\n* [[Caroline Still Anderson]], (class of 1878) \n*[[Lucinda L. Combs|Dr. Lucinda L. Combs Strittmater]], first female physician to serve in China for the Women's Foreign Ministry Society\n* [[Anandi Gopal Joshi|Anandibai Gopal Joshi]],Class of 1886, First Female Doctor from India\n* [[Jessie Crawford Wilson]], (class of 1890) Medical missionary to Persia.\n* [[Alice Bennett]], (class of 1880), chief physician and first woman superintendent of the women's department of the [[Norristown State Hospital|State Hospital for the Insane]] in Norristown, Pennsylvania.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cfmedicine.nlm.nih.gov/physicians/biography_32.html|title=Dr. (Mary) Alice Bennett|website=Changing the Face of Medicine|publisher=U.S. National Library of Medicine|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> \n* [[Elizabeth D. A. Cohen]], (class of 1857) first woman licensed to practice medicine in the state of [[Louisiana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/elizabeth-d-a-magnus-cohen|title=Elizabeth D.A. Magnus Cohen|website=JewishVirtualLibrary.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>\n* [[Rebecca Cole]], (class of 1867) the second African-American female physician in the United States.\n*[[Lucinda L. Combs]], (class of 1870) first female medical missionary in China, started first Women's Hospital in [[Peking]].\n* [[Halle Tanner Dillon Johnson]] the first female African-American doctor in [[Alabama]].\n* [[Caroline Matilda Dodson]] {class of 1874} (1845\u20131898), physician\n* [[Matilda Evans]], (class of 1897) the first African-American female physician licensed to practice in [[South Carolina]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://drexel.edu/now/archive/2017/March/Women-Physicians/|title=Remembering the Pioneering Women From One of Drexel\u2019s Legacy Medical Colleges|last=Falcone|first=Alissa|date=March 27, 2017|work=DrexelNow|access-date=2017-10-13|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Louise Celia Fleming]] (class of 1895) the first African-American female to attend and graduate.<ref name=\"BlackPast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpast.org/aah/fleming-louise-celia-lulu-1862-1899|title=Fleming, Louise Celia \"Lulu\" (1862-1899)|website=BlackPast.org|accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Eliza Ann Grier]], (class of 1897)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drexel.edu/medicine/About/Diversity/Our-Diverse-History/|title=Drexel University School of Medicine|website=Our Diverse History}}</ref> the first African-American female physician licensed to practice in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Rosetta Sherwood Hall]], (class of 1889) American-born Canadian medical missionary and educator in Korea.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich|url-access=registration|title=Notable American Women: The Modern Period : a Biographical Dictionary|last=Sicherman|first=Barbara|last2=Hurd Green|first2=Carol|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1980|isbn=978-0674627338|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich/page/299 299]\u2013300}}</ref>\n* [[Susan Hayhurst]], (class of 1857) the first woman to receive a pharmacy degree in the United States<ref>{{Cite journal|year=1911|title=Susan Hayhurst|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D0kfAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32|journal=American Journal of Pharmacy|volume=83|pages=32\u201339|access-date=November 29, 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* [[Sabat Islambouli]], first licensed female doctor in [[Syria]]<ref name=\"Rao\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/08/19th-century-women-medical-school_n_5093603.html|title=Meet The Three Female Medical Students Who Destroyed Gender Norms A Century Ago|last1=Rao|first1=Mallika|date=September 16, 2014|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Halle Tanner Dillon Johnson]], (class of 1891) the first woman to become a doctor in Alabama.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Verina Morton Jones|Verina M. Harris Morton Jones]] (class of 1888), the first woman licensed to practice in [[Mississippi]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Anandi Gopal Joshi]], (class of 1886) first Western-trained female physician to practice medicine in [[India]]<ref name=\"Rao\" />\n* [[Agnes Kemp]] (1823\u20131908), (class of 1879) the first woman to practice medicine in Dauphin County, Pennsylvania<ref name=Abram>Abram Ruth J. ''Send Us a Lady Physician: Women Doctors in America, 1835-1920''. WW Norton & Company, 1985, pp. 218\u2013220.</ref>\n* [[Anna Sarah Kugler]] (class of 1879) was the first medical missionary of the [[Evangelical Lutheran General Synod of the United States of North America]] and served in India for 47 years.\n* [[Clara Marshall]] (class of 1875), dean of Woman's Medical College from 1888 to 1917<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PBj5-zHEMvoC&lpg=PA216&pg=PA216|title=Biographical Dictionary of Modern American Educators|last1=Ohles|first1=Frederik|last2=Ohles|first2=Shirley M.|last3=Ramsay|first3=John G.|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|year=1997|isbn=9780313291333|page=[https://archive.org/details/biographicaldict0000ohle/page/216 216]|chapter=Marshall, Clara|access-date=December 1, 2016|via=Google Books|url=https://archive.org/details/biographicaldict0000ohle/page/216}}</ref>\n* [[Lillie Rosa Minoka Hill|Lillie Rosa Minoka-Hill]], (class of 1899) the second Native American woman to earn a medical degree.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Keiko Okami]], one of the earliest licensed female doctors in [[Japan]], the first being [[Ogino Ginko]]<ref name=\"Rao\" />\n* [[Susan La Flesche Picotte]], (class of 1889) the first [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] female physician<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Clara Swain]], (class of 1869) the first female medical missionary to India from the United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philadelphiaencyclopedia.org/archive/womans-medical-college-of-pennsylvania/|title=Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania {{!}} Encyclopedia of Greater Philadelphia|website=philadelphiaencyclopedia.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref>\n* [[Jennie Kidd Trout]], (class of 1875) first female licensed medical doctor in [[Canada]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Charlotte Whitehead]] Ross, a Canadian female physician who practiced in Montreal and Manitoba in the late 1800s and early 1900s.\n* [[Harriot Kezia Hunt]], Honorable MD recipient, women's rights activist, teacher.\n* [[Elizabeth Reifsnyder]], (class of 1881) opened first woman's hospital in [[Shanghai]]\n* [[Lilian Welsh]] (class of 1889), physician and educator, advocate for public health and preventative medicine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://msa.maryland.gov/msa/educ/exhibits/womenshall/html/welsh.html|title=Lilian Welsh, M.D., Maryland Women's Hall of Fame|date=2017|website=Maryland State Archives, Maryland Commission for Women|access-date=2017-11-15}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Holloway Wilhite]] (class of 1856), physician and philanthropist\n\n=== 20th century ===\n* [[Myrtelle Canavan]] (class of 1905), early neuropathologist who first described a form of leukodystrophy that would eventually be named after her, [[Canavan's disease]]. \n* [[Ruth Bleier]], (class of 1949) [[neurophysiologist]], and one of the first feminist scholars to explore how gender biases have shaped [[biology]].\n* [[Rita Sapiro Finkler]], (class of 1915) Ukrainian-born endocrinologist, gynecologist and pediatrician\n* [[Saniya Habboub]], (class of 1931) Lebanese medical doctor.\n* [[Joanne Overleese]], general surgeon, as well as one of the few doctors to have played in All-American Girls Professional Baseball League history\n* [[:de:Eva Reich|Eva Reich]], Austrian-born pediatrician and internationally known lecturer, daughter of controversial psychoanalyst [[Wilhelm Reich|Dr. Wilhelm Reich]].<ref>[http://archive.boston.com/bostonglobe/obituaries/articles/2008/08/13/dr_eva_reich_84_lectured_on_fathers_controversial_work/ \"Dr. Eva Reich, 84; lectured on father's controversial work,\" Boston Globe] (from the Associated Press), August 13, 2008.</ref>\n* [[Patricia Robertson]], a [[NASA]] astronaut and physician.\n* [[Kazue Togasaki]], (class of 1933) one of the earliest women of Japanese ancestry to earn a medical degree in the United States.\n* [[Martha Tracy]] (class of 1904), dean of Woman's Medical College from 1917 to 1940\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of defunct medical schools in the United States]]\n* [[List of female scientists before the 20th century]]\n* [[Penn Medical University]]\n* [[Women in medicine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==Further research==\n* [http://archives.drexelmed.edu/ Archives at Drexel University College of Medicine]\n* [http://www.saadigitalarchive.org/search/women%27s%20medical%20college%20of%20pennsylvania Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania materials in the South Asian American Digital Archive (SAADA)]\n* {{Facebook|id=Dr-Ellwood-Harvey-Underground-Railroad-Conductor-108263902552865|name=Dr. Ellwood Harvey, Underground Railroad Conductor}}\n\n{{coord|40.01190|-75.18420|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-PA|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Former women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:1850 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania| ]]\n[[Category:East Falls, Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "Halfirien", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumnae:Anandi Gopal Joshi -  deleted second listing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woman%27s_Medical_College_of_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "Caroline, Countess of Cranbrook", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n\n'''Caroline Gathorne-Hardy, Countess of Cranbrook''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (''n\u00e9e'' '''Jarvis'''; 18 December 1935) is an [[English aristocracy|English aristocrat]] and campaigner on [[food quality]] issues. She is the wife of [[Gathorne Gathorne-Hardy, 5th Earl of Cranbrook]].\n\nShe was born in London in 1935,<ref name=\"DID\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/dc976302#b00kmndy |title=Desert Island Discs - Castaway : Caroline, Countess of Cranbrook |work=[[BBC Online]] |publisher=BBC |accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Surman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/rural-life/profile-lady-caroline-cranbrook/30448.article |title=Profile: Lady Caroline Cranbrook |last=Surman |first=William |date=26 February 2010 |work=[[Farmers Guardian]] |accessdate=20 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714165512/http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/rural-life/profile-lady-caroline-cranbrook/30448.article |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> the daughter of Colonel Ralph George Edward Jarvis of [[Doddington Hall, Lincolnshire]] and his wife, Antonia Mary Hilda Meade.<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= [[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood]]|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink=Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=941|ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref> Both of her parents were in [[MI6]], and she moved to Portugal as a girl.<ref name=\"DID\"/>\n\nShe married the Earl of Cranbrook on 9 May 1967, and took up the married name Caroline Gathorne-Hardy. Their early home was in a jungle area of [[Peninsular Malaysia|Malaya]], where her husband worked as a zoologist.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> After three years, they took up residence at his family seat, Great Glemham House, [[Great Glemham]], Saxmundham, Suffolk.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> She ran the estate farm and raised their three children.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> When her husband inherited the [[Earl of Cranbrook|earldom of Cranbrook]] from his father, on 22 November 1978, she became a [[Countess]].<ref name=\"Surman\" />\n\nShe was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 2004, for services to the red [[meat industry]], after campaigning to save local [[abattoirs]].<ref name=\"Surman\" /><ref name=\"Hart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3663232/Eco-hero.html|title=Eco hero - Telegraph|last=Hart|first=Carolyn|date=17 February 2007|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> She is president of the [[Aldeburgh Food and Drink Festival]].<ref name=\"Surman\" />\n\nLady Cranbrook appeared as a \"castaway\" on the [[BBC Radio]] programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on 31 May 2009,<ref name=\"DID\"/> and received [[The Oldie]]'s 'Campaigner of the Year' Award in 2010.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> The [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]] has called her \"the doughtiest fighter for good sense in agriculture\".<ref name=\"Surman\" />\n\nShe and her husband have three children:<ref name=\"burke\"/> \n*John Jason Gathorne-Hardy, Lord Medway (born 26 October 1968), heir apparent to the Earldom, born in [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n*Dr. Lady Flora Gathorne-Hardy (born 10 October 1971)\n*Hon. Argus Edward Gathorne-Hardy (born 28 May 1973)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cranbrook, Caroline}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:People from Suffolk Coastal (district)]]\n[[Category:English countesses]]\n[[Category:English farmers]]\n[[Category:Women farmers]]\n[[Category:Food activists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n\n{{nobility-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n\n'''Caroline Gathorne-Hardy, Countess of Cranbrook''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (''n\u00e9e'' '''Jarvis'''; 18 December 1935) is an [[English aristocracy|English aristocrat]] and campaigner on [[food quality]] issues. She is the wife of [[Gathorne Gathorne-Hardy, 5th Earl of Cranbrook]].\n\nShe was born in London in 1935,<ref name=\"DID\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/dc976302#b00kmndy |title=Desert Island Discs - Castaway : Caroline, Countess of Cranbrook |work=[[BBC Online]] |publisher=BBC |accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Surman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/rural-life/profile-lady-caroline-cranbrook/30448.article |title=Profile: Lady Caroline Cranbrook |last=Surman |first=William |date=26 February 2010 |work=[[Farmers Guardian]] |accessdate=20 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714165512/http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/rural-life/profile-lady-caroline-cranbrook/30448.article |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> the daughter of Colonel Ralph George Edward Jarvis of [[Doddington Hall, Lincolnshire]] and his wife, Antonia Mary Hilda Meade.<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= [[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood]]|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink=Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=941|ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref> Both of her parents were in [[MI6]], and she moved to Portugal as a girl.<ref name=\"DID\"/>\n\nShe married the Earl of Cranbrook on 9 May 1967, and took up the married name Caroline Gathorne-Hardy. Their early home was in a jungle area of [[Peninsular Malaysia|Malaya]], where her husband worked as a zoologist.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> After three years, they took up residence at his family seat, Great Glemham House, [[Great Glemham]], Saxmundham, Suffolk.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> She ran the estate farm and raised their three children.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> When her husband inherited the [[Earl of Cranbrook|earldom of Cranbrook]] from his father, on 22 November 1978, she became a [[Countess]].<ref name=\"Surman\" />\n\nShe was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 2004, for services to the red meat industry, after campaigning to save local [[abattoirs]].<ref name=\"Surman\" /><ref name=\"Hart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3663232/Eco-hero.html|title=Eco hero - Telegraph|last=Hart|first=Carolyn|date=17 February 2007|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> She is president of the [[Aldeburgh Food and Drink Festival]].<ref name=\"Surman\" />\n\nLady Cranbrook appeared as a \"castaway\" on the [[BBC Radio]] programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on 31 May 2009,<ref name=\"DID\"/> and received [[The Oldie]]'s 'Campaigner of the Year' Award in 2010.<ref name=\"Surman\" /> The [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]] has called her \"the doughtiest fighter for good sense in agriculture\".<ref name=\"Surman\" />\n\nShe and her husband have three children:<ref name=\"burke\"/> \n*John Jason Gathorne-Hardy, Lord Medway (born 26 October 1968), heir apparent to the Earldom, born in [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n*Dr. Lady Flora Gathorne-Hardy (born 10 October 1971)\n*Hon. Argus Edward Gathorne-Hardy (born 28 May 1973)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cranbrook, Caroline}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:People from Suffolk Coastal (district)]]\n[[Category:English countesses]]\n[[Category:English farmers]]\n[[Category:Women farmers]]\n[[Category:Food activists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n\n{{nobility-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kku", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkmeat industryusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caroline,_